spanGrp.span: The elders told me; they told me that they all came from a place called China Kicha.
Sigegl-wa t ys paga-l (_) t ys she jie-wa kable beteu r k' ki China Kicha
My grandma, my mom came from China Kicha;
Es mamita es mina-wa je beteu r China Kicha wa
that China Kicha is located in the Perez Zeledon area.
Je China Kicha jata-n r Perez Seledon jam gataga
My grandpa is Indian; he is from our land, which is located in the Talamanca area.
Es tatiga je r sa k' wak je r sa k' ska Je k' jata-n kom k' ki Talamanka (_)
My grandpa came from there and married my grandma in China Kicha.
(_) je-wa es tatiga beteu je jula gug es mamita m China Kicha wa
They came to this place called Ujarraz.
Je n beteu ji Ujarras k' kie jegepi
In our language in Spanish it is called Ujarraz; in our language it is called Sk.
se je kt' wa k' kww m ji (_) sikwa kt' wa kie Ujarras
in our language it is called Sk.
Se je kt' wa je kie r Sk
The other people call us [people] from Sk.
Pe kww t se je kie r Sk-wa
They tell me that once they got to Ujarraz to this savannah, there were lots of trees, nances, espavels, white cane, and a tree called kskl.
Jie-wa t ys page jirpa beteu (_) Ujarras wa tara ji Sk kengla k' klabe biggle je r ka (r) kal eb kal ki be'k kal ki kit kal ki (r) kal ki juk r kal ki jiebi tsta ki k'skl'
There were lots of deer, and a lot of food and meat to eat. There was a lot of meat in the bush, not like now that we have to buy everything with money.
Je ts t' ji k' inga Sk eb jiebi t' mulurbe ts yek ts a-n yek (r) yek ts kata-n yek ts jiebi k' dek jrga Ka r jira gepi se jen kable t r t'-le ngl wa
Long ago, there was that on this earth; they came here, bought cows, pigs, hens from the whites.
K''_jira je ts-ka ji k' krwa blali inga sa sa ts ji ska-ra jie-wa beteu ji ska-ra jeska (_) jie-wa t baga t' kuchi t' kabayu t' shkoro t' je r sikwa-wa
There were no roads, no electricity; it was all dark. The Ceibo River was the way we see it now.
Ka ala ta ka lus se'i ta pa K' r katuir ye eb Bikis blali sa t s-g (_) gepi
The elders say that there was no nice road and there were lots of weird beings who made us lose the way.
Sigegl-wa t page jiebi jeska ra ka ala ta b shk-gl T bichi sisulo t se je ala se je ala shw-g se w n
When we were ill, there was no such thing as a hospital, as the whites call it.
Se dw-g-ra sikwa kt' wa ka (_) ospital ta
Instead, there were the best healers who could cure all illnesses.
Jera jeska ra jaw-wa ts kl-l b (_) dwe inga Je t pe dw-g (_)
Then, the Catholic church, it came, it baptized us.
Jera la Iglesia Katolika je beteu je t se (_) wjoge-wa
Many people were so. They were not baptized.
The ancestors lived like that, blind.
The elders tell me that there was nothing in the savannah, like, say, bananas.
sigegl-wa t ys page jiebi ji ska kable Sk blali ra ka jir kun ta ka jir kuna chom bi ke-le (_)
They came and there were two clans, the one called Julablwa and the one called Kibeiglwa;
Jie-wa (_) beteu-lo dits' r b-ol dits' (_) kie Julablwa (_) dits' (_) kie Kibeiglwa
these clans came from afar, from our homeland, Talamanca.
je dits' (_) beteu k' kom sa k' ska Talamanka
Our families are there; our real roots are there.
Je-wa (_) jeska se gicha-wa ts jen r se je turi-wa chgl
They also tell me that they married another clan there;
jeme ys page-ite jiebi jeska jula gug dits' (_) kww (_)

and our clan came from there, so they say; there is a road in the mountain, in the Guanacaste area; it is the road that comes from our homeland and they also say that when we had to buy salt or sweets, we had to walk long distances because there was no road; there was nothing, as there is now.

Jen ska sa ditsi beteu jie-wa t sa page (_) ala blali k'bata Guanakaste shebe wa jam wa m ala blali je daj plaja sa k' ska Jeme she-ite sa (_) jiebi sa mi-g (_) deye t' bi jir blota t' gepi sa jen shk r kom Ka ala ta Ka jir ta menbi sa t s-g jir gepi
The elders used to live well;
they say that when they went to work, they would make chicha, but not like nowadays.
sigegl-wa t page jiebi jie-wa m-g-ra shkabl-ra jie-wa t di ble-g ka r jir blegu-n gepi kuna
They would make chicha for planting corn, beans, rice, and everything to eat and drink;
Jie-wa t di ble-g r kw kgl ken kgl arros kgl jir biggle ya-n -n
The women would grind on stones to make the chicha.
alagl-wa mi-g-n je w' jak inga kw w' di ble-n
Nowadays we have forgotten all that.
Jiskara sa t jiskara sa t kable shww-ka
They told me that many years ago they lived well.
Jie-wa t she s- (_) k''_jira jie-wa sen-l b
There were no fights, all the rivers were clean; people were clean;
Ka (_) ka arige ta Kable digl ts r sigin Sers-wa ts sigin
there were no people like those from today, that is, ill-intentioned.
Ka yuru kuna ta ji (m) se je ts gepi jr slu ta eb
They also tell us that when children were born, the women would not fuck around;
Jeme sa page-ite jiebi jie-wa yabla d-g-ra alagl-wa bi ra jie-wa ka m kuna se klinama yekwenama ts jrga kuna
they would bear the children in our village.
Jie-wa yabla bt-g r ji se je k jrga
They would build houses far away with banana and brar leaves, and there they would give birth to their children.
Se je male m-g j yuw k' kom chom k' wa (_) brar k' wa Jeska yabla bt-g wa
They had to be cured; as they whites say, Id say, they had to wait for three times during two weeks. Then they would go back home.
Jeska jen jula bts jeska kian sikwa kt' wa she ys t ra jeska kian' (_) (_) begets-pa (_) kiks-pa mt-b (_) dg kinse dia bi Jeskara bt-g j ga
The elders say that long ago our first ancestors came to Ujarraz; they worked a lot; and many of them passed away; some are buried, so they say, and they tell it very well.

Jebi sigegl-wa t page k''_ji se je gicha-wa se je ksei sgt-wa-ra ji wa de (r) de-le jiska Ujarras ka r jir sa t jie-wa (r) (_) jie-wa shkbl t mnle ka skn mnle ts-ka (m) ble-le spk jrga Jebi jie-wa t page jie-wa t page b
If you want to know more, ask the elders, the ones with gray hair; they are the best story-tellers. They suffered many illnesses;
Bas w kik (r) kksa-gle (_) bas w k kian ksen--n bas m chag sigegl-wa ts-ka tsg srr jie-wa n t b wa page Jira ka se kuna de yunaga t jie-wa (_) inga (m) (_)
todays illnesses send the elders to heaven, where they come from.
Ji de ts je t se sigegl-wa patk-er-ka Sur k' ska m bete ska
if there is anything else to ask, you should ask the elders.
jir kian wchag-n sigegl-wa n chag-gl (_)
They, who lived long ago, know better, not like us, young people, who also know the history but the elders know it much better.
Jera (_) jie-wa sen k''_ji jera jie-wa w jer b ka r se je dats dulagle-wa Sa wl jer btsn sa t sigegl-wa k gug (_) (_) t ra atara gicha btsn siw' jr bitsn je r sigegl-wa ka
The elders have already fought evil.
(_) Je bele-ka bichi ra sha-bla ys t
You should ask them and listen to them.
Jera jen (_) wchag-w bas t (m) Je kse kable bas t
That is all I can tell you.
